{"key":"processedPost-11891928","value":{"id":11891928,"first":11891218,"last":11892347,"when":1264372090,"utime":"01/25/10 12:28 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>chumdog said:</b><br />k thanks <img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/smile.gif\" alt=\":smile:\" title=\":smile:\"/> so when pressure guage reaches zero it is relativley safe to open the cooker and take the jars out to cool at room temp. got it thanks <img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/smile.gif\" alt=\":smile:\" title=\":smile:\"/><br /></blockquote><br /><br />No, you should wait for it to cool down more.&nbsp; If you open too soon, you will lose moisture in the jars.&nbsp; You don't need to wait until it's totally cool, but you don't want to take steaming hot jars out of the PC either.&nbsp; If you do, that steam that's trying to escape has to go somewhere, and the path is through your filter, which gets it damp.&nbsp; A damp filter is a path for contaminants to colonize to your substrate.&nbsp; A good rule of thumb is if you can put the tenderest part of your wrist on the side of the cooker and not get burned, it's cool enough to open safely.&nbsp; <br /><br />When it's going to take two to three weeks for a jar to colonize, nothing is gained by trying to jump ahead by an hour or two.&nbsp; It just doesn't make sense.<br />RR","title":"Re: pressure cooker cool down","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}